3. HDMI System Design and Architecture

3.1 Airframe and Propulsion

· Configuration: Blended wing‑body with variable‑geometry wings.
  · Wingspan: 5.2 m (extended loiter) / 2.4 m (swept intercept).
  · Length: 4.5 m; MTOW: 2,500 kg.
· Materials: Carbon‑fibre composites with titanium reinforcements. Morphing mechanism uses electromechanical actuators and shape‑memory alloy backups.
· Propulsion:
  · Two 150 kW electric ducted fans (battery: 80 kWh Li‑S, 30 h endurance).
  · One ramjet (JP‑10, 800 kg fuel) for Mach 3.2 dash, 1,500 km range.
  · Thrust vectoring nozzles (±20°) for high agility.

3.2 Sensor Suite

Sensor Type Performance
Radar AESA X‑band 250 km detection (1 m² RCS), 200 tracks
EO/IR Multi‑spectral turret 4K visible, 1 MP IR, 50 km recognition
LIDAR Solid‑state flash 5 km range, 10 cm accuracy
Acoustic 32‑microphone array 30 km launch detection
Nuclear HPGe gamma + He‑3 neutron 500 m detection range

3.3 Computing Hardware

· Photonic Processor: Lightmatter Envise‑2 (2 PFLOPS equivalent, 8 GB HBM2e).
· Electronic Processor: Xilinx Versal Premium (ARM + GPU + FPGA, 100 TFLOPS).
· Quantum Co‑processor: 80‑qubit superconducting chip (Rigetti) with compact cryocooler.
· Storage: 2 TB NVMe SSD (encrypted) + 4 TB mission data recorder.

3.4 Communications

· Quantum Link: Free‑space QKD (BB84), 100 km LOS, 1 Mbps key rate.
· Tactical Links: Link 16, SATCOM (Ka‑band), UHF/VHF SDR.
· Mesh Network: 60 GHz IEEE 802.11ad for UAV‑to‑UAV, 2 Gbps.

3.5 QUENNE Integration

The QUENNE layers are implemented as containerised microservices communicating via DDS. The TRIAD AI runs on the electronic processor, while low‑level sensor processing is offloaded to the photonic core. Quantum algorithms are invoked only when needed (optimisation, key exchange). The Linux core ensures real‑time performance and security.

